Normally it would look like:
  MockedGPIOReader& mockPresenceGPIO = static_cast<MockedGPIOReader&>(psu.getPresenceGPIO());
  EXPECT_CALL(mockPresenceGPIO, read).WillOnce(Throw(std::runtime_error{"error"}));
  // Do stuff to cause the read() ...

But since this is a constructor, you can't call the getPresenceGPIO() method.  If the function that creates the MockedGPIOReader returned a static singleton, you could do it.  However, that might lead to other problems, since all the PSUs in test cases would be sharing a single MockedGPIOReader.

You can make a mock function throw with 'Throw', like from device_tests.cpp in phosphor-regulators:

     EXPECT_CALL(*action, execute)
         .WillRepeatedly(Throw(TestSDBusError{"Unable to set sensor value"}));

